cm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjIwMDQxMjh9/ed2b91f0b720eb=
3383c7fd7ba77c3a5db6e74fd43f3928c09f0de2c88a873215" style=3D"color:#d40000;=
text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">told</a></u> me in Oct=
ober, even before <b>Kamala Harris</b>=E2=80=99s loss, that last summer=E2=
=80=99s excruciating but ultimately successful effort to oust Biden from th=
e ticket gave a green light to younger generations (plural, because that=E2=
=80=99s how old some of these members are) to challenge their elders in Dem=
ocratic primaries this next election cycle. Yes, some of this is what we=E2=
=80=99ve always seen: young-ish men and women in a hurry. But something dee=
per is going on here with the committee situation. <br/><br/>After the Bide=
n drama and the <b>Feinstein</b> drama=E2=80=94not to mention <b>Ruth Bader=
 Ginsburg</b>=E2=80=99s decision to not retire, which led to a third Trump =
Supreme Court appointment=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s apparent that previously def=
erential Democrats view patience as a luxury they can no longer afford. So =
generational warfare is
breaking out <i>well</i> ahead of schedule, as Democrats stare down the bar=
rel of exile from the White House and minority status on Capitol Hill. For =
some contemplating how best to stand up to Trump, the torch-passing can=E2=
=80=99t come soon enough, and the committees could be where it starts=E2=80=
=94even if some of those torches are seized by force.<br/></td>
